<div id="p796" class="blockpost roweven">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#2&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=796#p796">2009-11-15 13:04:47</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=90618">sys_err</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Member</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: Bittorrent future research area</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<p>I have some ideas about future research areas...<br /><br />We need to share not constant objects sometimes. In example: everyday or weekly snapshots, VCS repositories, big ebook libraries. I think that it is very useful to add some features as like as rsync features in bittorrent protocol for handling such sharing.<br /><br />Let's M the &quot;root&quot; peer for file F (100Mb). &quot;root&quot; means that M and only M can change F and share these changes. Another peers M1, M2,... can not do that.<br /><br />Let's M1 and M2 had completely downloaded F, and M3 had downloaded only first 1Mb of F.<br /><br />Let's M bit change F now. He change bytes with order number 5000000, 5000001, and add 10Kb at end of F.<br /><br />How M can share this new file F effectively? &quot;effectively&quot; means that<br /><br />1) torrent tracker need to be notify that M1 and M2 can't share changed blocks.<br />2) M1 and M2 need to download only 10Kb + 2b and start to share new F<br />3) M3 don't need to know that some changes have been made. His downloading from M1 and M2 (and may be sharing to M4) not stopped.<br /><br />(sorry for bad english...)</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
			<div class="postfootleft"><p>Offline</p></div>
			<div class="postfootright"><div>&nbsp;</div></div>
		</div>
	</div>
</div>

